The `ClaWDProvider` is a standalone agentic provider that wraps Composio tools into the Clawd MCP-compatible `ClaWDTool` format — no `@composio/core` runtime dependency required.

**Core types**
```typescript
interface ClaWDTool {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  schema: { type: 'object'; properties: Record<string, unknown>; required?: string[] };
  category: string;
  execute: (args: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<unknown>;
}

interface ClaWDToolkit {
  tools: ClaWDTool[];
  toMCPToolDefs(): Array<{ name: string; description: string; inputSchema: ... }>;
  call(toolName: string, args: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<unknown>;
}
```

**Three ways to get a toolkit**

1. **Wrap existing Composio tools** (you already have the tool list + executor):
```typescript
import { claWDProvider } from './mcp/src/composio/clawd-provider.js';
const toolkit = claWDProvider.wrapTools(composioTools, executeToolFn);
```

2. **Build from native tool definitions** (define your own tools inline):
```typescript
const toolkit = claWDProvider.buildNativeToolkit(myTools, myExecuteFn);
```

3. **Fetch a Composio-hosted MCP toolkit** (calls Composio's MCP endpoint):
```typescript
const toolkit = await claWDProvider.fetchMCPToolkit(); // uses COMPOSIO_API_KEY
```

**Running an agent loop**
```typescript
const result = await claWDProvider.runClaWDAgent(toolkit, 'Buy 100 USDC of SOL on Jupiter');
```
The agent loop tries `XAI_API_KEY` first (Grok function calling), then falls back to `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (Claude tool use). It keeps looping on tool calls until the model produces a final text response.

**Why zero runtime deps**: The provider replicates only the Composio interfaces it needs, so `clawd-code` and `mcp/` stay lightweight with no additional npm installs required.

Here's a complete walkthrough using `@clawd/zk-client`:

```typescript
import { ClawdZkClient, computeNullifier, buildPublishPublicInputs } from "@clawd/zk-client";
import { createSolanaRpc } from "@solana/kit";
import { PublicKey } from "@solana/web3.js";

const rpc = createSolanaRpc(process.env.CLAWD_ZK_RPC_URL!);
const client = new ClawdZkClient({
  rpc,
  programId: new PublicKey("CLAWDzk11111111111111111111111111111111111"),
  photonUrl: process.env.CLAWD_ZK_RPC_URL, // Helius doubles as Photon
});

// 1. Derive nullifier from attester secret + context
const nullifier = computeNullifier({
  secret:  signerKeypair.secretKey.slice(0, 32),
  context: "solana-clawd/model/v1",
});

// 2. Build the instruction
const ix = await client.publishAttestation({
  signer:            signerKeypair.publicKey,
  modelHash:         modelHashBytes,    // Uint8Array(32)
  payloadCommitment: commitmentBytes,   // Uint8Array(32)
  nullifier,
  proof: groth16Proof,                  // { a, b, c, verifyingKey }
});

// 3. Sign and send (standard @solana/kit)
const tx = new Transaction().add(ix);
const sig = await sendAndConfirmTransaction(connection, tx, [signerKeypair]);
console.log("Attestation published:", sig);
```

The client internally: derives the nullifier address, fetches a non-inclusion validity proof from Photon, packs Light CPI accounts, and returns the fully-assembled instruction. You just sign and send.

The fastest path is `ClawdZkAgent.fromEnv()` — it reads config from environment variables and you go straight to calling methods:

```typescript
import { ClawdZkAgent } from "@clawd/zk-agent";

// Set env vars before running:
// export CLAWD_ZK_RPC_URL=https://mainnet.helius-rpc.com/?api-key=...
// export CLAWD_ZK_KEYPAIR=~/.config/solana/id.json

const agent = await ClawdZkAgent.fromEnv();

// Attest a model
const result = await agent.attestModel({
  modelHash:         modelHashBytes,
  payloadCommitment: payloadBytes,
  proof:             groth16Proof,
  context:           "my-model/v1",
});
console.log(result.nullifierHex);  // registered nullifier
console.log(result.summary);       // human-readable description

// Or use the natural-language router (no model call — pure regex)
import { routeIntent, dispatchRoute } from "@clawd/zk-agent";
const route = routeIntent("verify this proof", agent, { proofPath: "./p.json" });
const r = await dispatchRoute(route, agent);
```

Required env:
```bash
CLAWD_ZK_RPC_URL=https://mainnet.helius-rpc.com/?api-key=YOUR_KEY
CLAWD_ZK_KEYPAIR=/path/to/keypair.json   # optional, for signing
```

Each instruction has a specific field order. All fields are padded to exactly 32 bytes.

**`publish_attestation`** (4 fields = 128 bytes):
```typescript
import { buildPublishPublicInputs } from "@clawd/zk-client";
const inputs = buildPublishPublicInputs({
  attester:          signer.publicKey.toBytes(),  // [0] 32 bytes
  modelHash,                                       // [1] 32 bytes
  payloadCommitment,                               // [2] 32 bytes
  nullifier,                                       // [3] 32 bytes
});
```

**`consume_attestation`** (3 fields = 96 bytes):
```typescript
import { buildConsumePublicInputs } from "@clawd/zk-client";
const inputs = buildConsumePublicInputs({
  consumer:            signer.publicKey.toBytes(), // [0] 32 bytes
  attestationAddress,                              // [1] 32 bytes
  consumeNonce,                                    // [2] 32 bytes
});
```

**`commit_encrypted_state`** (4 fields = 128 bytes):
```typescript
import { buildCommitPublicInputs } from "@clawd/zk-client";
const inputs = buildCommitPublicInputs({
  committer:            signer.publicKey.toBytes(), // [0] 32 bytes
  modelHash,                                         // [1] 32 bytes
  ciphertextCommitment,                              // [2] 32 bytes
  version: 1n,          // [3] u64 little-endian, zero-padded to 32 bytes
});
```

The Rust on-chain helper functions (`build_public_inputs`, etc. in `lib.rs`) produce the same ordering, so the circuit, client, and on-chain verifier stay in sync.

The `zk-primitives/` directory publishes two npm packages:

**`@clawd/zk-client`** (low-level SDK)
```typescript
// Nullifier
import { computeNullifier, computeNullifierBatch, deriveNullifierAddress,
         NULLIFIER_PREFIX } from "@clawd/zk-client/nullifier";

// Proof assembly
import { buildPublishPublicInputs, buildConsumePublicInputs,
         buildCommitPublicInputs, serializeProof,
         verifyGroth16Offchain } from "@clawd/zk-client/proof";

// Light Protocol helpers
import { fetchValidityProofV2, fetchAddressTreeV2,
         fetchRandomStateTreeV2, packAccounts } from "@clawd/zk-client/state";

// Orchestrator
import { ClawdZkClient } from "@clawd/zk-client";
```

**`@clawd/zk-agent`** (agent wrapper + CLI)
```typescript
import { ClawdZkAgent, routeIntent, dispatchRoute,
         loadAgentConfig, KNOWN_INTENTS } from "@clawd/zk-agent";
```
Also ships `clawd-zk-agent` CLI binary with subcommands: `inspect`, `attest`, `commit`, `verify`, `nullifier`, `ask`.

Install both:
```bash
npm install @clawd/zk-client @clawd/zk-agent
```
